North Korea has already launched three confirmed ICBMs and only two since July 14th, 2017. North Korea launched one ICBM on July 28th, 2017 and another on November 28th, 2017. Since 2017 there haven't been any specific North Korean missile tests since there hasn't been a missile test in almost ten months it seems unlikely that North Korea would test another land-based intercontinental ballistic missile. These developments seem to support the idea that North Korea has changed policy since the heightened tensions between the US and North Korea. Since the US announced a summit between the two powers, North Korea has promoted economic initiatives over military force. North Korea has also sought greater cooperation and unity from South Korea and appears to be dismantling rocket test sites. It's still uncertain if the peace talks will yield any results but with the possibility of a second summit, a laxation of the US embargo on the North Korean economy, and a lack of displaying any ICBMs at the DPRK's 70th anniversary it seems very unlikely that North Korea will launch another ICBM. If negotiations stall then North Korea may resume its test launches.

This is seen most recently in North Korea not displaying any ICBMs in their 70th anniversary military parade September 10th and the reportedly "very warm letter" sent by Kim Jung Un to President Trump requesting a second meeting.

According to CNN, North Korea has launched two ICBMs so far since 14 July 2017. One was launched on 28 July 2017 (Hwasong-14) and another on 29 November 2017 (Hwasong-15). In the span of 5 months, 2 were launched and since there's been no other launches of ICBMs. Due to the summit between Donald Trump and Kim Jong Un and improved relations between the two, I predict that North Korea will not launch any more ICMBs before 31 Dec 2018. Additionally, North Korea did not display any ICBMs in a military parade held early September (see bbc link), which could be a positive result of the dialogue between the two leaders in the 2018 North Korea - United States summit.

Already seen 2, their 2nd on 28 July 2017 and 3rd on 29 Nov 2017. All 3 DPRK ICBM tests occurred in 2017 - 0 so far in 2018, given Kim's other, ongoing political gains. But is it a stretch that after 3 tests in 2017 we'll see more in 2018, after the Singapore summit hubbub dies down? Some might claim this is even more likely to occur, several months after the summit, perhaps to bring an adversary back to the table. If 0 or 1 tests in second half of 2018, that's the 2-3 range, but seeing 2 subsequent tests may be more likely than we'd like to assume. Note the remaining DPRK holidays: Fatherland Victory Day 27 July, Liberation Day 15 Aug, founding day 9 Sept, not to mention New Year's Eve and the possibility of a test coinciding with a Xi speech, a Donald speech, US Nov midterms, etc. If not sooner than end of year, a "Hwasong-16" might be 2019 news.

The current count is 2. No launches have taken place since last November, and since 2013, they have averaged a missile test (not necessarily ICBM) every 90 days or so. This means based on the time remaining, we'd expect about 2 additional launches given the overall trend. If we assume all launches will be ICBMs, which is not a slam dunk assumption - only 3 of the last 6 launches have been ICBMs - we'd expect the total to be 4 by the end of December. However, we'll take the more recent trend of about half of missile tests being ICBMs. Additionally, with the progress on peace talks on the peninsula, the risk of missile tests has become greater for North Korea, perhaps contributing to the lack of tests in 2018 so far.

Apparently NK already had launched 2-3 and I have been predicting based on the question how it is still worded...oops. Disappointing to have missed that just by lack of participation in the social media portion of predicting. A friendly reply just set me straight. Even when I don't mess it up like on this one the questions seem each year to almost never present opportunities to demonstrate actual strategic predictions, only chrono-based or numeric-based predictions among a known set of potential answers. A random choice of responses could probably score ok just by way of the potential answers being limited to a predetermined set of answers. Maybe I should make a cow pie bingo board for each question to make it at least more entertaining! I guess I feel I need a new type of challenge that has no scoring or ranked competition but instead asks for individually or group-derived predictions of events and conditions for potential events that are not yet on the media radar (i.e. what questions should we be asking now...in 6 months etc in this geographic region or globally etc). I'm not interested in or talented at reading all possible media and GJP thread posts and coalescing into a prediction among a known set...I and others are talented at using our experience and knowledge in specific geographic regions and in specific industries/ fields to predict the future developments that are simply not yet on the media radar or developed enough to form a questions with a set of known predetermined answers from which to choose a prediction. I guess they would serve two different purposes and both helpful but I am simply not interested in most of these GJP questions as stated anymore and feel they do not give any opportunity to use my knowledge of the world to make actual strategic predictions (i.e. Russia's role in middle east in last years...I and many others had many discussions about this in the GJP threads last year and even earlier, but we are just now seeing a lot of numeric/ chrono-based after-the-fact questions about the very events we were predicting in the thread discussions). The way the Russia challenge questions are now stated a monkey pulling answers out of a hat would literally have a decent chance at being a middle scorer.

I have changed my forecast and updated it as Kim Jong Un's claim to commit to no more testing of nuclear weapons was announced along with President Trump agreeing to meet with him and discuss current relations and goals moving forward. I think this is fascinating, as we see an attempt by North Korea to comply with the majority of the international community, and this will greatly affect the decisions of neighboring countries, such as Japan militarizing, as the presence of a threat may no longer remain, and working towards better relations with both Koreas.

The preparations for the meeting will take some time; I'd guess at least a month, possibly longer (excited to find out). Any launches in the meantime are highly unlikely; even if the meeting would go bad, this significantly lowers the probability for multiple tests during 2018.

http://www.nti.org/analysis/articles/north-koreas-hwasong-12-missile-stepping-stone-icbm/ When North Korea tested the Hwasong-12 on May 14th, it became clear that this was an entirely new missile, with a new engine and improved design characteristics. The Hwasong-12 is not itself an intercontinental ballistic missile (ICBM), but it displayed all the technologies necessary to build a missile that can strike the United States. Its range is estimated to be about 4,500 km with a nuclear-weapon-sized payload (500 kg), falling short of the 5,500 km range that defines an ICBM. When North Korea tested an ICBM a few weeks later on July 4th, it used the same engine and underlying technologies first seen in the Hwasong-12. If we wish to understand North Korea's ICBM program, we must start with the Hwasong-12.
